{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:35:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:35:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17927"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17927"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.48,0,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76757"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10641"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24790"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76757"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old male was noticed to be confused in a shopping mall. The paramedics who attended noticed the medical ID he was wearing stating he is a Type 1 diabetic. His blood glucose level was 2.7mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common cause of hypoglycaemia in patients with type 1 diabetes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Missed meals","Excessive insulin administration","Alcohol consumption","Increased physical activity","Infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with type 1 diabetes, the most common cause of hypoglycaemia is \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcessive insulin administration\u003C/strong\u003E. This can occur due to errors in dosing or timing of insulin injections relative to meals and physical activity. In this scenario, the patient\u0027s confusion with a low blood glucose level, are indicative of hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMissed meals\u003C/strong\u003E can also lead to hypoglycaemia, especially if insulin doses are not adjusted accordingly. However, the primary issue is often the mismatch between insulin and carbohydrate intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased physical activity\u003C/strong\u003E can increase insulin sensitivity and lead to hypoglycaemia if insulin doses are not adjusted. While this is a contributing factor, it is not the most common cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hypoglycaemia by inhibiting gluconeogenesis, but it is less common than insulin-related causes in type 1 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfection\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes hyperglycaemia due to stress responses and increased insulin resistance, rather than hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypoglycaemia in patients with type 1 diabetes is most commonly caused by excessive insulin administration.","Other factors contributing to hypoglycaemia include missed meals, increased physical activity, and alcohol consumption.","Recognising and managing hypoglycaemia is crucial to prevent severe complications."],"references":["Cryer PE. Hypoglycemia in type 1 diabetes mellitus. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2010 Sep;39(3):641-54. doi: 10.1016/j.ecl.2010.05.003. PMID: 20723825; PMCID: PMC2923455.","Choudhary P, Amiel SA. Hypoglycaemia in type 1 diabetes: technological treatments, their limitations and the place of psychology. Diabetologia. 2018 Apr;61(4):761-769. doi: 10.1007/s00125-018-4566-6. Epub 2018 Feb 8. PMID: 29423581; PMCID: PMC6448988.","DiMeglio LA, Evans-Molina C, Oram RA. Type 1 diabetes. Lancet. 2018 Jun 16;391(10138):2449-2462. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31320-5. PMID: 29916386; PMCID: PMC6661119","Lucier J, Mathias PM. Type 1 Diabetes. 2024 Oct 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939535","Giwa AM, Ahmed R, Omidian Z, Majety N, Karakus KE, Omer SM, Donner T, Hamad ARA. Current understandings of the pathogenesis of type 1 diabetes: Genetics to environment. World J Diabetes. 2020 Jan 15;11(1):13-25. doi: 10.4239/wjd.v11.i1.13. PMID: 31938470; PMCID: PMC6927819","Kahanovitz L, Sluss PM, Russell SJ. Type 1 Diabetes - A Clinical Perspective. Point Care. 2017 Mar;16(1):37-40. doi: 10.1097/POC.0000000000000125. PMID: 28943810; PMCID: PMC5606981"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17927"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62250"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T07:39:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T08:05:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76757"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"se